    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-20T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="129"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d129">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 Naval Armaments/102: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName
                            corresp="#p_GHS1" type="from">Gibson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-20T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 20, 1932—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 20—5:53 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>262. In accordance with the question which you raised over the telephone of what
                    the British might be able to accept in the cruiser category and the various
                    observations between us in accordance with your talk, I submit for your
                    consideration a phraseology: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The limitation placed by the London Naval [Treaty?] upon the cruiser
                            class represented a drastic reduction in actual tonnage or in the
                            projected programs of the signatory powers. However, if corresponding
                            reductions are accepted by other naval powers and the program here
                            proposed is carried into effect, the United States is prepared to accept
                            a further blank per cent cut in its treaty cruiser tonnage as soon as
                            the adjustments can be made which will permit <pb facs="0315" n="195"
                                xml:id="pg_195"/> the other treaty powers to make corresponding
                            reductions. Hence, I propose that we proceed to further reductions in
                            the cruiser class to bring it into harmony with the reductions here
                            proposed for other naval categories at the time of the revision of the
                            London Treaty in 1935 or earlier if possible”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GHS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
